797
00:44:24,422 --> 00:44:26,220
Scott: And some other people didn't see it for, like, minutes.

798
00:44:26,480 --> 00:44:27,251
Rym: Well, I see where you're going.

799
00:44:27,271 --> 00:44:27,900
Rym: I think I agree.

800
00:44:28,020 --> 00:44:34,480
Scott: So it's like what they don't want to make it hard to solve just by being obtuse or, you know, obfuscated.

801
00:44:34,821 --> 00:44:36,760
Scott: They want to make it hard to solve by solving.

802
00:44:36,900 --> 00:44:45,280
Scott: But if you don't make it hard to solve by obfuscating, then it becomes really hard to make something that is hard, right?

803
00:44:45,420 --> 00:44:46,485
Rym: And that's my problem.

804
00:44:46,666 --> 00:44:50,160
Rym: I brute-forced every puzzle, almost every puzzle, by not even thinking.

805
00:44:50,460 --> 00:44:51,284
Rym: Here's my process.

806
00:44:51,545 --> 00:44:53,614
Rym: I go into a room, I look at all the places.

807
00:44:53,674 --> 00:44:55,080
Rym: I can throw portals that are angled.

808
00:44:55,680 --> 00:44:55,862
Scott: Yep.

809
00:44:56,085 --> 00:44:57,440
Scott: And you know that you're going to jump out of those.

810
00:44:57,520 --> 00:45:01,378
Rym: And then later when there's goop, I also think, "Do I want to put a portal there or goop

811
00:45:01,398 --> 00:45:01,579
Rym: there?".

812
00:45:01,920 --> 00:45:02,422
Rym: And you know what?

813
00:45:02,743 --> 00:45:07,320
Rym: I put goop everywhere I could, except the one place where you can put it fucking everywhere and it doesn't matter.

814
00:45:07,441 --> 00:45:07,506
Rym: Yep.

815
00:45:07,880 --> 00:45:10,040
Rym: Because that always solved by brute force.

816
00:45:10,160 --> 00:45:16,700
Rym: If there's any place where an angle thing goes toward a place where I can get goop, I wouldn't even look at what was on the other side.

817
00:45:17,060 --> 00:45:23,740
Rym: I would just blindly put the goop, throw the portal, jump through it, because every jump was guaranteed to get me where I wanted to be.

818
00:45:23,900 --> 00:45:26,040
Scott: Or at least somewhere different that you hadn't been before.

819
00:45:26,080 --> 00:45:27,260
Rym: That I had to get to to solve it.

820
00:45:27,260 --> 00:45:28,679
Scott: Unless you've already taken that jump.

821
00:45:28,900 --> 00:45:33,480
Rym: I could assume that any jump would take me exactly where I needed to go.

822
00:45:33,780 --> 00:45:33,903
Scott: Right.

823
00:45:33,923 --> 00:45:34,699
Scott: And what were they going to do?

824
00:45:34,820 --> 00:45:41,480
Scott: If they would have put in extra angled surfaces that went to places you didn't want to go, then it would basically just be obtuse.

825
00:45:41,721 --> 00:45:44,995
Scott: You would go somewhere and then it would be like, "Oh derp, there's no reason to go over here.

826
00:45:45,015 --> 00:45:45,497
Scott: It's just a red

827
00:45:45,517 --> 00:45:45,839
Scott: herring.".

828
00:45:46,181 --> 00:45:47,190
Scott: And that doesn't make it harder.

829
00:45:47,231 --> 00:45:48,200
Scott: That just makes it annoying.

830
00:45:48,320 --> 00:45:52,240
Rym: But at the same time, because there are no red herrings, I didn't have to think.

831
00:45:52,340 --> 00:45:57,780
Rym: As soon as I saw any way to combine two elements together, that seems to be the secret.

832
00:45:58,481 --> 00:46:01,860
Rym: Any two elements, if you can combine them together, is guaranteed to be the solution.

833
00:46:02,163 --> 00:46:03,940
Rym: So I've got goop and an angled surface.

834
00:46:04,160 --> 00:46:07,519
Rym: Alright, I'll go through the angled surface on a portal, hit the goop, it'll bounce me where I need to go.

835
00:46:08,220 --> 00:46:08,887
Rym: Button and a cube.

836
00:46:09,089 --> 00:46:10,020
Rym: Cube's going on the button.

837
00:46:10,240 --> 00:46:10,600
Scott: That's right.

838
00:46:11,500 --> 00:46:13,140
Rym: As soon as two elements link up, it just works.

839
00:46:14,541 --> 00:46:22,680
Rym: And too many of the puzzles also, because even if they had multiple steps, they made it really hard to go to the wrong area.

840
00:46:23,281 --> 00:46:27,760
Rym: So as a result, you would never have to actually figure out the order of the steps.

841
00:46:27,840 --> 00:46:29,289
Rym: It was always the direct route.

842
00:46:29,772 --> 00:46:31,020
Rym: You didn't have to do anything tricky.

843
00:46:31,381 --> 00:46:38,880
Scott: Yeah, there were some puzzles in Portal 1, maybe a couple of them, where you could actually go to the next room.

844
00:46:39,340 --> 00:46:44,300
Scott: But you couldn't actually do anything to progress in that room because you hadn't done the previous room.

845
00:46:44,500 --> 00:46:48,255
Rym: Or you could get all the way to the end and then realize, "Oh, I didn't do a cube

846
00:46:48,275 --> 00:46:48,416
Rym: thing.".

847
00:46:49,520 --> 00:46:55,080
Scott: Right, but in Portal 2, there was no way to get to the next area until you had already solved the first part.

848
00:46:55,220 --> 00:46:56,279
Scott: So they broke it into chunks.

849
00:46:56,741 --> 00:47:02,020
Scott: So it's like they made the user -- it's like if you were trying to make -- think about making an operating system.

850
00:47:02,140 --> 00:47:03,080
Scott: You're making a user interface.

851
00:47:03,520 --> 00:47:06,320
Scott: So you design -- you have the best user interface design in the world.

852
00:47:06,740 --> 00:47:09,215
Scott: So anyone who wants to do something, it's like, "Oh, I want to burn a CD.

853
00:47:09,316 --> 00:47:09,658
Scott: Oh, that was

854
00:47:09,718 --> 00:47:09,899
Scott: easy.".

855
00:47:10,162 --> 00:47:11,052
Scott: "I want to visit a website.

856
00:47:11,092 --> 00:47:11,335
Scott: That was

857
00:47:11,416 --> 00:47:11,598
Scott: easy.".

858
00:47:11,840 --> 00:47:15,000
Scott: And just everything is so obvious, it's like the best user interface known to man.

859
00:47:15,580 --> 00:47:16,859
Scott: But then you want to make it challenging.

860
00:47:17,902 --> 00:47:21,380
Scott: How do you make it challenging but also make it good design at the same time?

861
00:47:21,420 --> 00:47:24,008
Scott: And that is the fundamental thing in Portal.

862
00:47:24,410 --> 00:47:27,620
Scott: is that you want -- how do you make it harder without making it bad design?

863
00:47:27,860 --> 00:47:32,500
Rym: Now luckily, you know, it sounds like we're scathingly reviewing the game as being too easy.

864
00:47:32,640 --> 00:47:33,551
Rym: Oh, it was so fun.

865
00:47:33,692 --> 00:47:34,239
Scott: It was so fun.

866
00:47:35,321 --> 00:47:37,800
Scott: I want more friggin' chambers so badly.

867
00:47:37,840 --> 00:47:41,720
Rym: This is a situation of, you know, that's the only criticism we have.

868
00:47:42,200 --> 00:47:46,400
Scott: Yeah, the game makes you -- it's weird because it's like the game makes you feel smart, right?

869
00:47:47,401 --> 00:47:54,158
Scott: But it's like the fact that they make the Portal, you know, the puzzles intentionally not hard, it's sort of like, "No, you're really not so

870
00:47:54,178 --> 00:47:54,340
Scott: smart.".

871
00:47:54,340 --> 00:47:56,560
Rym: Well, here's one final complaint.

872
00:47:56,660 --> 00:48:00,300
Rym: And this is actually something that is weird because in Portal 1 there was more of this.

873
00:48:00,700 --> 00:48:05,100
Rym: And I remember being frustrated because it was very difficult in some places.

874
00:48:05,400 --> 00:48:08,380
Rym: But in Portal 2 they removed it and I was more frustrated that it was gone.

875
00:48:08,900 --> 00:48:10,853
Rym: Execution doesn't matter for 99% of the puzzles.

876
00:48:12,241 --> 00:48:16,560
Rym: You have infinite time, you just sit there like, "Portal, Portal, Portal," do your thing.

877
00:48:17,241 --> 00:48:18,533
Rym: Figuring it out is 90% of the battle.

878
00:48:19,680 --> 00:48:24,380
Rym: There are very few times you had to shoot a Portal mid-air and then change Portals after you pop through.

879
00:48:25,320 --> 00:48:33,939
Rym: And many puzzles, while you didn't need to do that, because I guess I'm good at FPSs, I skipped a number of Portal puzzles.

880
00:48:34,363 --> 00:48:35,420
Scott: With execution skill?

881
00:48:35,620 --> 00:48:39,520
Rym: Just by using execution skill and making a loop where I'd fall from the sky into a pit.

882
00:48:39,882 --> 00:48:43,800
Rym: And I'd just do this a bunch and then I'd bounce off of something and fly off across everything.

883
00:48:44,180 --> 00:48:48,440
Scott: The co-op actually has a lot of execution-type puzzles.

884
00:48:48,880 --> 00:48:49,720
Rym: I rescind my criticism.

885
00:48:49,860 --> 00:48:57,800
Scott: For example, there's one where one person has to go basically onto this moving platform behind a wall of glass, right?

886
00:48:58,261 --> 00:49:02,340
Scott: And the other person has to step on buttons to basically play Gyromite.

887
00:49:03,088 --> 00:49:03,520
Scott: Oh man.

888
00:49:03,780 --> 00:49:06,460
Scott: And if you fail at the Gyromite, spiky death for the other guy.

889
00:49:06,827 --> 00:49:07,075
Scott: Oh man.

890
00:49:07,421 --> 00:49:12,520
Scott: And you have to do the timing of the button pressing to save the other guy from Gyromite, spiky death.

891
00:49:12,940 --> 00:49:16,700
Scott: So that's just one example of the kind of execution puzzles that exist in co-op.

892
00:49:16,900 --> 00:49:22,840
Scott: Another example of execution in co-op, a lot of times you have to do something simultaneously with the other guy, with timing.

893
00:49:23,500 --> 00:49:30,699
Scott: And it's like, so you'll... The game lets you display a timer on the screen that'll count down for both of you at the same time.

894
00:49:31,140 --> 00:49:32,876
Scott: So it'll be like three, two, one.

895
00:49:33,320 --> 00:49:35,460
Scott: And then you both hit the buttons and go into your Portals.

896
00:49:35,842 --> 00:49:38,420
Scott: And you have to do something at the same time to make it work.

897
00:49:39,260 --> 00:49:42,876
Scott: So there is a lot of that sort of Evangelion episode, DDR stuff.

898
00:49:43,840 --> 00:49:45,540
Rym: Ah, that's a good episode and a good reference.

899
00:49:46,160 --> 00:49:54,900
Rym: But along these lines, the portions in between chambers where there's plot going on, like Wheatley's yelling at you or something, were a little too railed.

900
00:49:55,881 --> 00:50:04,680
Rym: In that, in Portal 1, once you got behind the scenes, there was really a lot of leeway and a lot of very tricky execution toward the end.

901
00:50:04,680 --> 00:50:07,720
Rym: So Portal 2, those were actually the easiest parts of the game.

902
00:50:07,880 --> 00:50:11,700
Rym: Because if you see a wide surface, you shoot a fucking Portal at it, it's almost guaranteed to be the answer.

903
00:50:12,280 --> 00:50:14,700
Scott: Yeah, because they only had one place that you could actually go.

904
00:50:14,720 --> 00:50:16,040
Rym: Yeah, you couldn't jump on the rails.

905
00:50:16,321 --> 00:50:19,100
Scott: Well that is one thing, atmospherically, right?

906
00:50:19,160 --> 00:50:22,540
Scott: It's like Portal 2 had the same kind of humor as Portal 1, right?

907
00:50:22,700 --> 00:50:34,460
Scott: But the addition of the Wheatley character took away, while the humor was the same, and was, you know, excellently written and voice acted and executed and all that, right?

908
00:50:34,980 --> 00:50:40,960
Scott: The atmosphere was different because you weren't alone with GLaDOS.

909
00:50:41,820 --> 00:50:43,040
Scott: It was much noisier.

910
00:50:43,821 --> 00:50:45,090
Rym: Only in some areas.

911
00:50:45,131 --> 00:50:46,320
Rym: I would have noticed, I mean, remember?

912
00:50:46,661 --> 00:50:49,779
Scott: No, because when Wheatley goes away, Cave Johnson comes in.

913
00:50:50,202 --> 00:50:51,580
Rym: No, but he's not there that often.

914
00:50:51,742 --> 00:50:52,280
Rym: He's there a lot.

915
00:50:52,321 --> 00:50:53,000
Rym: And he's not interacting.

916
00:50:53,903 --> 00:50:55,800
Rym: Alright, I guess at this point we're at the spoiler line.

917
00:50:55,900 --> 00:50:58,353
Rym: So, if you have not yet played Portal 2, play it.

918
00:50:59,600 --> 00:51:01,099
Rym: And if you haven't played Portal 1, play it.

919
00:51:01,701 --> 00:51:04,059
Scott: It's not really, I mean, it's not really spoilable.

920
00:51:04,220 --> 00:51:06,619
Rym: I'll warn people, because I'm going to spoil a few things.

921
00:51:07,100 --> 00:51:12,359
Rym: And, you know, I understand that a spoiler can affect someone's enjoyment of something, even though it's not, anyway.

922
00:51:13,301 --> 00:51:14,060
Rym: We're going to spoil shit.

923
00:51:14,140 --> 00:51:15,653
Rym: So if you haven't played the game, one, what are you doing?

924
00:51:15,693 --> 00:51:16,460
Rym: listening to GeekNights?

925
00:51:16,700 --> 00:51:18,100
Rym: Portal's way more fun than GeekNights.

926
00:51:18,180 --> 00:51:19,999
Scott: Maybe they're doing it at the same time.

927
00:51:21,040 --> 00:51:33,000
Rym: So, there was, because in this game there was the Wheatley part of the game, and the GLaDOS part of the game, the End part of the game, and the Cave Johnson part of the game, and they all had very different atmospheres.

928
00:51:33,861 --> 00:51:34,685
Rym: And I liked that.

929
00:51:34,745 --> 00:51:37,480
Rym: I liked that the atmosphere was different in all these areas.

930
00:51:38,280 --> 00:51:44,720
Rym: Because Portal 1 was really one atmosphere halfway through, and then the back of that atmosphere for the other half.

931
00:51:45,601 --> 00:51:48,260
Rym: So I'm glad they did something different, just because it was something different.

932
00:51:48,400 --> 00:51:54,200
Rym: And I think one of the primary, like, the game itself is really good, but I wouldn't enjoy it nearly as much.

933
00:51:54,300 --> 00:52:00,640
Rym: I would say a good third of the enjoyment of Portal is just the fact that it is really well written, and really immersive, and really fucking funny.

934
00:52:01,343 --> 00:52:03,260
Scott: You know, it's funny, but it's not that funny.

935
00:52:03,440 --> 00:52:07,740
Rym: I was laughing out loud during pretty much the entirety of the Cave Johnson era.

936
00:52:07,900 --> 00:52:11,240
Scott: I think ponies are about twice as funny as Portal 2.

937
00:52:11,240 --> 00:52:16,496
Rym: When Cave Johnson is just arguing, he's like, "Yeah, but don't worry, you're not in the control group.

938
00:52:16,696 --> 00:52:17,579
Rym: Those guys broke all their

939
00:52:17,599 --> 00:52:17,839
Rym: legs.".

940
00:52:18,801 --> 00:52:22,520
Rym: I'm being told by the scientists that I shouldn't have told you that you're not in the control group.

941
00:52:22,640 --> 00:52:23,083
Rym: What do they know?

942
00:52:23,123 --> 00:52:25,480
Rym: I found that stuff to be hilarious.

943
00:52:25,820 --> 00:52:27,616
Scott: Yeah, you know, it got me a slight chuckle.

944
00:52:28,180 --> 00:52:33,560
Rym: Did you find all the doors, like the secret area with all the extra doors of all the vitrified experiments?

945
00:52:34,181 --> 00:52:38,480
Scott: I looked around a little bit, but I didn't spend the time to actually look in every single nook and cranny.

946
00:52:38,500 --> 00:52:38,842
Rym: It was trivial.

947
00:52:38,862 --> 00:52:42,380
Rym: There's one office, right, where there's a door hidden half behind a bunch of computers.

948
00:52:42,824 --> 00:52:44,799
Rym: And back there, there's a whole bunch of doors.

949
00:52:45,480 --> 00:52:50,660
Rym: And every door has the audio of whatever experiment, like "Turn your blood into peanut oil" was back there.

950
00:52:50,780 --> 00:52:51,620
Scott: Oh, I didn't go back there, no.

951
00:52:51,840 --> 00:52:52,144
Rym: Oh, really?

952
00:52:52,245 --> 00:52:53,320
Rym: You should have gone back there.

953
00:52:53,420 --> 00:52:58,220
Rym: You also, apparently, we were talking before the show, didn't find the dry dock to the Borealis.

954
00:52:58,600 --> 00:52:59,263
Scott: No, I didn't either.

955
00:52:59,283 --> 00:53:02,820
Scott: But I remembered the Borealis from Half-Life 2, but I didn't find it in Portal 2.

956
00:53:02,820 --> 00:53:05,620
Rym: You didn't find the turrets practicing their song.

957
00:53:05,700 --> 00:53:07,265
Scott: Well, look, the turrets singing, right?

958
00:53:07,667 --> 00:53:08,249
Scott: I found this.

959
00:53:08,349 --> 00:53:11,700
Scott: I knew that in that chamber, there's one turret behind a grating.

960
00:53:11,821 --> 00:53:13,371
Scott: And I'm like, "There's something back there.

961
00:53:13,613 --> 00:53:14,479
Scott: I know there's something back

962
00:53:14,519 --> 00:53:14,620
Scott: there.".

963
00:53:14,640 --> 00:53:15,163
Scott: And I tried.

964
00:53:15,183 --> 00:53:15,987
Scott: I was like, "Poke, poke.

965
00:53:16,509 --> 00:53:17,173
Scott: Poke, poke, poke.

966
00:53:18,017 --> 00:53:18,359
Scott: Egg.".

967
00:53:18,379 --> 00:53:18,660
Scott: Whatever.

968
00:53:18,900 --> 00:53:20,279
Scott: And I basically gave up and kept going.

969
00:53:20,360 --> 00:53:21,299
Rym: You know how I got back there?

970
00:53:22,569 --> 00:53:23,160
Rym: You kept poking?

971
00:53:23,520 --> 00:53:26,160
Rym: No, there's a laser in that area, too, right?

972
00:53:26,962 --> 00:53:30,020
Rym: I angled the laser in and blew up the turret, and it blew the grating off.

973
00:53:30,844 --> 00:53:31,679
Scott: Oh, son of a bitch.

974
00:53:31,820 --> 00:53:33,460
Rym: And then I went in there and there's the turret singing.

975
00:53:33,761 --> 00:53:37,680
Scott: I tried to poke and look around behind the turret to see if there was a portable surface.

976
00:53:38,322 --> 00:53:43,120
Rym: The other easter egg area was the one place where the containment field's busted.

977
00:53:43,820 --> 00:53:44,258
Scott: Yeah, I did that.

978
00:53:44,440 --> 00:53:46,391
Rym: Yeah, I walked through and it's like, "The containment field is

979
00:53:46,431 --> 00:53:46,753
Rym: broken.".

980
00:53:46,793 --> 00:53:47,979
Rym: And I stop, and I'm like...

981
00:53:48,100 --> 00:53:51,033
Scott: And you see a portable wall right there, and you're like, "I'm going to get the

982
00:53:51,053 --> 00:53:51,133
Scott: cube.".

983
00:53:53,064 --> 00:53:54,680
Rym: I didn't notice the portable wall.

984
00:53:54,800 --> 00:53:57,558
Scott: So you went all the way back, and you were like, "Oh shit, I gotta do the puzzle

985
00:53:57,598 --> 00:53:57,799
Scott: again?".

986
00:53:57,980 --> 00:54:04,479
Rym: No, so I went back, and I basically looped and looped and looped to jump over there with the cube.

987
00:54:05,564 --> 00:54:06,720
Scott: You could've just brought the cube up.

988
00:54:06,760 --> 00:54:07,780
Rym: And I did all this work.

989
00:54:07,880 --> 00:54:11,319
Scott: If you had just made a portal before you went down, you could've just grabbed the cube.

990
00:54:11,740 --> 00:54:14,820
Rym: So I do this crazy, bullshit, tactical execution shenanigans.

991
00:54:15,320 --> 00:54:19,257
Rym: I get the cube through, and then as I walk in, I see the wall, and I'm like, "Oh,

992
00:54:19,498 --> 00:54:19,658
Rym: wow.".

993
00:54:20,684 --> 00:54:23,300
Scott: The thing is, you have to make a wall before you jump down.

994
00:54:23,460 --> 00:54:28,320
Scott: I almost jump down without making the portal first, in which case you have to solve the puzzle again.

995
00:54:28,581 --> 00:54:30,340
Rym: I did that a couple of times later in the game.

996
00:54:31,240 --> 00:54:35,780
Rym: I think my favorite puzzles were the ones involving the goop and the tractor beams.

997
00:54:37,024 --> 00:54:37,589
Scott: I like that.

998
00:54:37,609 --> 00:54:38,920
Rym: you can put the goop in the tractor beams.

999
00:54:39,282 --> 00:54:41,900
Scott: The tractor beams are called extrusion funnels.

1000
00:54:42,563 --> 00:54:44,779
Scott: I actually like the bridges the most.

1001
00:54:46,280 --> 00:54:50,059
Rym: Especially when you can put them sideways and block turrets, or knock turrets over.

1002
00:54:50,420 --> 00:54:57,640
Scott: The thing is, I wish that they would've gotten... First of all, did you notice in Portal 1, there were the energy balls?

1003
00:54:58,143 --> 00:54:59,881
Scott: The energy balls are not present in Portal 2.

1004
00:54:59,881 --> 00:55:01,580
Rym: I didn't like the energy balls.

1005
00:55:01,740 --> 00:55:02,720
Scott: What's wrong with the energy ball?

1006
00:55:03,462 --> 00:55:10,860
Rym: They remind me very much of the puzzles you start to get about halfway through Lolo 3.

1007
00:55:10,860 --> 00:55:17,420
Rym: Where they'd run out of good ideas, and the puzzles started to rely on fiddly execution of discrete things.

1008
00:55:17,580 --> 00:55:21,220
Rym: There's a thing that's moving around, and you have to also interact with that.

1009
00:55:21,542 --> 00:55:24,720
Scott: The energy ball is very functionally similar to the laser.

1010
00:55:25,081 --> 00:55:29,020
Scott: But it is subtly different from the laser, in that there's just one energy ball.

1011
00:55:29,120 --> 00:55:36,960
Rym: But the laser, by being consistent, and being aligned, and especially with the way you can use the lenses, I think was a more elegant puzzle mechanism.

1012
00:55:37,100 --> 00:55:42,320
Scott: The thing with the laser is that if you have a laser with a portal, you have to keep the portal open for the laser.

1013
00:55:43,181 --> 00:55:49,640
Scott: For the energy ball, you can get the energy ball into the place it's supposed to go, and then your portals are free again.

1014
00:55:49,740 --> 00:55:52,157
Scott: You don't need to keep putting the energy ball back into its spot.

1015
00:55:52,197 --> 00:55:52,520
Scott: It's there.

1016
00:55:52,920 --> 00:55:57,800
Rym: I guess with the extrusion funnels, I really enjoyed getting goop in places where they probably didn't expect me to get goop.

1017
00:55:58,421 --> 00:56:06,358
Scott: No, I actually, from what I saw, is that they pretty well constructed the levels so that you couldn't really get goop anywhere.

1018
00:56:06,678 --> 00:56:07,520
Scott: that would sort of cheat.

1019
00:56:08,160 --> 00:56:15,456
Scott: I'm sure the YouTube will prove me wrong, but from what I could tell, it was pretty tricky to get goop somewhere.

1020
00:56:15,476 --> 00:56:17,420
Scott: that would really break the level.

1021
00:56:17,800 --> 00:56:26,358
Rym: Yeah, but when I got to the white goop, because they told you what the other two goops do, and you get to the white goop, and it's just coming out, and I'm looking at them like, "White goop, I wonder what this

1022
00:56:26,438 --> 00:56:26,920
Rym: does.".

1023
00:56:27,481 --> 00:56:38,500
Scott: Yeah, the white goop really, they put it in there because it was clever, but you really can't make any good puzzles with the white goop because basically once you get the white goop somewhere, you can get it everywhere.

1024
00:56:38,980 --> 00:56:43,460
Rym: Nope, it depends entirely on the angle of attack from the white goop source.

1025
00:56:43,760 --> 00:56:46,960
Rym: If the angle is such, then there are many places you could not get goop.

1026
00:56:47,000 --> 00:56:55,260
Scott: But the thing is, when you get the white goop somewhere, you can get it almost everywhere, and if you can get the white goop almost everywhere, then you can solve whatever puzzle there is.

1027
00:56:55,380 --> 00:57:01,100
Rym: Notice how, as a result, there are only a few puzzles with the white goop, and they were actually probably the best puzzles you could make with the white goop.

1028
00:57:01,100 --> 00:57:04,480
Scott: That was probably all the puzzles you could make with the white goop, that wouldn't just be stupid.

1029
00:57:04,480 --> 00:57:07,120
Rym: Short of having much larger puzzles.

1030
00:57:07,580 --> 00:57:23,260
Scott: Yeah, I mean, you could use a lot of gratings, because notice goop doesn't stick to a grating, to contain the white goop to certain areas, and then force someone to get the white goop to go through an extrusion funnel to a weird place on a bridge where the late, you know, you could do tricky stuff like that.

1031
00:57:24,123 --> 00:57:29,080
Rym: They have good puzzles with turning on and off the goop versus the funnels versus other stuff, too.

1032
00:57:29,500 --> 00:57:38,060
Scott: Yeah, I wish, though, that they could have made, you know, something more complex, like, you know, the balls hard super meat boy kind of funnels, right?

1033
00:57:38,100 --> 00:57:45,900
Scott: Because super meat boy manages to be balls hard in execution and combination of moves, right?

1034
00:57:46,341 --> 00:57:52,020
Scott: And the portal, too, they get pretty far with combination of moves, but they don't actually go as far as you can get.

1035
00:57:52,281 --> 00:57:58,120
Scott: There's nothing that combines goop and lasers and funnels and bridges simultaneously, right?

1036
00:57:58,522 --> 00:58:00,480
Scott: There's nothing that does all of them at the same time.

1037
00:58:00,560 --> 00:58:06,360
Scott: I think there's one part where you have to put goop on a bridge, and I think that's as complicated as it gets, right?

1038
00:58:06,600 --> 00:58:11,700
Scott: But there's no goop on a bridge with a funnel and both colors of goop and a laser.

1039
00:58:11,940 --> 00:58:15,751
Rym: Well, once you got orange goop, all the puzzles for a while were anytime.

1040
00:58:15,791 --> 00:58:18,719
Rym: there's a long stretch, you're just gonna run into a portal.

1041
00:58:19,080 --> 00:58:24,678
Scott: Well, I like the ones, actually, where you use orange goop and two portals to pick up speed in a very small area, right?

1042
00:58:25,300 --> 00:58:26,485
Scott: Because that's pretty tricky.

1043
00:58:26,565 --> 00:58:36,700
Scott: And then, those happen more often in the co-op, because when you're going through, when you're picking up speed in a small area with the orange goop, you need somebody else to control the portals to launch you somewhere.

1044
00:58:36,840 --> 00:58:37,798
Scott: You can't do it on your own.

1045
00:58:38,720 --> 00:58:40,064
Rym: Of course, I got through a lot of puzzles.

1046
00:58:40,124 --> 00:58:45,900
Rym: by shooting a portal in between the two portals I was gaining up speed on in, like, the half a second you've got.

1047
00:58:46,221 --> 00:58:48,320
Scott: Yeah, I did a lot of that, too, where it wasn't necessary.

1048
00:58:48,340 --> 00:58:55,615
Rym: I would walk through and, like, look and practice until I could snap my view to the exact spot I had to hit from the angle.

1049
00:58:55,695 --> 00:58:58,060
Rym: I would see it in through the portal.

1050
00:58:58,760 --> 00:59:04,920
Scott: I would do a lot where you'd shoot a portal, you'd sort of poke halfway through it, and then you would shoot a portal while you're hanging out of the portal.

1051
00:59:04,960 --> 00:59:06,499
Rym: Yup, and pop out, just like you shoot and pop.

1052
00:59:06,720 --> 00:59:08,971
Scott: And then you pop backwards to end up where you just shot.

1053
00:59:09,534 --> 00:59:10,700
Scott: That's always a good trick.

1054
00:59:12,120 --> 00:59:17,007
Rym: But, I don't know, story-wise, it picked up well.

1055
00:59:17,828 --> 00:59:27,119
Rym: It fit the continuity, except that unless you read that comic, there's a huge gap, and the comic is a little too literal of, "Oh, here's exactly what happened between the two

1056
00:59:27,139 --> 00:59:27,520
Rym: games.".

1057
00:59:27,760 --> 00:59:28,878
Scott: Yeah, I don't know.

1058
00:59:29,120 --> 00:59:30,460
Rym: But, did you read the comic?

1059
00:59:30,620 --> 00:59:31,940
Scott: Yeah, I did read the comic, and the extras.

1060
00:59:32,241 --> 00:59:35,889
Scott: Yeah, I mean, you know, the plot is the plot.

1061
00:59:35,950 --> 00:59:37,774
Scott: It's not exactly the most exciting plot.

1062
00:59:37,854 --> 00:59:39,799
Scott: It's just something, you know, to carry.

1063
00:59:40,880 --> 00:59:46,180
Rym: I like the end where you're carrying GLaDOS on the potato, and I love how she hates that fucking bird.

1064
00:59:47,320 --> 00:59:54,440
Rym: And I just love how Wheatley, he seems so nice until GLaDOS is kind of like, you realize what he is, right?

1065
00:59:54,645 --> 00:59:54,860
Scott: Yeah.

1066
00:59:55,000 --> 00:59:58,277
Rym: And then after that, when he's like, "Oh, God, he's playing classical

1067
00:59:58,317 --> 00:59:58,679
Rym: music.".

1068
00:59:59,080 --> 00:59:59,301
Rym: Yeah.

1069
00:59:59,742 --> 01:00:03,171
Scott: But, you know, the thing is, the plot really itself is like, whatever.

1070
01:00:03,552 --> 01:00:05,437
Scott: You know, the Half-Life 2 plot, I care about.

1071
01:00:05,497 --> 01:00:06,800
Scott: The Portal 2 plot, I don't care.

1072
01:00:06,980 --> 01:00:10,640
Scott: But, they intertwine, and they're going to, at least, if Half-Life 2 Episode 3 ever exists.

1073
01:00:10,721 --> 01:00:11,400
Rym: Well, the Borealis.

1074
01:00:11,800 --> 01:00:12,241
Scott: Exactly.

1075
01:00:12,342 --> 01:00:15,671
Scott: If they ever come out with the next game, it'll intertwine.

1076
01:00:16,173 --> 01:00:18,540
Scott: But, the plot is basically just a vehicle.

1077
01:00:19,082 --> 01:00:20,980
Rym: I wonder if Cave Johnson became the G-Man.

1078
01:00:21,261 --> 01:00:25,820
Scott: Maybe, but all of the, you know, the plot is just a vehicle for all the jokes, right?

1079
01:00:25,900 --> 01:00:35,220
Scott: It's like, you know, the real thing about the story that makes it entertaining is, you know, the potato and, you know, all the, you know, space.

1080
01:00:36,320 --> 01:00:41,760
Scott: But, and the only, the plot is just something that they can attach all those things onto, right?

1081
01:00:41,860 --> 01:00:45,993
Scott: The plot itself is, you know, sort of just like a train.

1082
01:00:46,033 --> 01:00:48,240
Scott: But, what really matters is the cargo on the train.

1083
01:00:48,400 --> 01:00:48,581
Rym: Yup.

1084
01:00:48,961 --> 01:00:50,665
Rym: The end, I thought, was really touching.

1085
01:00:50,745 --> 01:00:57,240
Rym: Like, the ending movie, the whole, the only complaint I have about the very end is that the boss fight was a trivial joke.

1086
01:00:57,701 --> 01:00:58,999
Scott: The boss fight was a trivial joke.

1087
01:00:59,080 --> 01:01:00,300
Rym: I just kind of, I walked around, no urgency.

1088
01:01:00,300 --> 01:01:03,016
Scott: The Portal 1 boss fight actually was slightly hard.

1089
01:01:03,037 --> 01:01:03,600
Scott: You would die.

1090
01:01:03,840 --> 01:01:04,081
Scott: Yeah.

1091
01:01:04,402 --> 01:01:06,350
Rym: It took me, like, three or four attempts to beat the Portal 1.

1092
01:01:06,350 --> 01:01:08,779
Rym: Portal 2, I literally was like, dupe, dupe, dupe, dupe.

1093
01:01:09,480 --> 01:01:16,200
Rym: I wish, instead of railroading you, where basically it lays you where you can't move, and then suddenly there's the moon up there.

1094
01:01:16,801 --> 01:01:23,380
Rym: I wish you had, in the course of the fight, blown up the ceiling and just had to fucking notice the moon and wonder if you could shoot a portal at it.

1095
01:01:23,480 --> 01:01:27,459
Rym: I wish, I wish they'd made you figure that out instead of just giving it to you.

1096
01:01:27,880 --> 01:01:31,006
Scott: I wish that they would have had an alternate ending, right?

1097
01:01:31,066 --> 01:01:37,900
Scott: So, you know, by default, you know, it would just be you fight the thing and you smash it and then you get the ending.

1098
01:01:38,261 --> 01:01:46,600
Scott: But, if you were clever and noticed the moon through the ceiling sometime during the fight, you could have gotten the secret ending that way.

1099
01:01:46,800 --> 01:01:48,180
Scott: That would have been, that would have been cooler.

1100
01:01:49,140 --> 01:01:52,820
Rym: That little bit at the end, while it's the, it is the cake is a lie of this game.

1101
01:01:53,560 --> 01:01:53,682
Scott: Space!

1102
01:01:53,702 --> 01:01:55,400
Scott: I actually like space better than cake is a lie.

1103
01:01:55,662 --> 01:01:56,560
Rym: Space is really funny.

1104
01:01:56,820 --> 01:01:58,018
Scott: Especially since it was foreshadowed.

1105
01:01:58,540 --> 01:02:07,480
Rym: But it's just, I don't know, there's something about it, that little yellow guy who keeps coming by is like, the one time, I think it's the second time, he's like, we're in space, and Wheatley's like, I know, I know.

1106
01:02:07,801 --> 01:02:14,440
Scott: Yeah, in the commentary, they actually talked about how they were originally gonna have, uh, it wasn't gonna be just Wheatley, it was gonna be a whole bunch of different ones.

1107
01:02:14,820 --> 01:02:30,680
Scott: But they couldn't find a way to actually introduce all of them to you and make it still stick, so they stuck with just Wheatley, and some of those, like the cowboy and the space guy, those guys were basically originally gonna have much more of a, you know, they were gonna, all these little balls would have had equal footing in the game.

1108
01:02:31,120 --> 01:02:34,440
Scott: But they ended up just using Wheatley for the whole game and sticking the rest of them at the end.

1109
01:02:34,460 --> 01:02:35,380
Rym: That's fine, Wheatley was pretty funny.

1110
01:02:35,380 --> 01:02:36,280
Scott: That was definitely a good move.

1111
01:02:36,340 --> 01:02:47,120
Rym: Wheatley was way funnier later, when he, like, in the early part, when he's just kind of talking at you, it wasn't that funny, but afterward, and little things, like in the beginning, when he's like, you know, say something, prove you don't have brain damage.

1112
01:02:47,602 --> 01:02:47,977
Scott: And you jump.

1113
01:02:48,600 --> 01:02:51,580
Rym: It gives you all the cues for like, what button to hit, and it tells you to hit jump.

1114
01:02:51,860 --> 01:02:55,600
Scott: Yeah, and he's like, alright, you jumped, you know, you jumped there, yeah, that was pretty good.

1115
01:02:56,840 --> 01:03:08,720
Scott: But yeah, you gotta play Portal 2, it was one of the best designed games there is, you know, but it's just, the only complaint, pretty much, is that we're hardcore, and it's not challenging enough for our hardcore-ness.

1116
01:03:09,040 --> 01:03:15,340
Scott: At least Half-Life 2, you can put it on balls hard mode, where like, you get killed instantly by a guy with a crossbow.

1117
01:03:15,460 --> 01:03:17,480
Rym: Of course, look at Portal 1, it had the challenge chambers.

1118
01:03:17,941 --> 01:03:25,980
Scott: But the thing is about challenge chambers is that those aren't different puzzles, they're just, it's like the puzzles aren't harder, they just want you to solve them very quickly.

1119
01:03:26,440 --> 01:03:32,760
Scott: It's like, I don't want to solve it faster, I want to solve it, I want to solve something that is harder to solve, I want to spend like a good 20 minutes.

1120
01:03:32,760 --> 01:03:37,860
Rym: Alright, well Bionic Commando had that, I couldn't beat even a fucking quarter of those challenges in Bionic Commando.

1121
01:03:38,380 --> 01:03:39,920
Scott: Yeah, that's a good example, I like those though.

1122
01:03:40,341 --> 01:03:49,480
Scott: But I want a Portal chamber that takes me a good 15, 20 minutes to figure out, but is not hard in an obtuse way, but is hard in a Super Meat Boy way.

1123
01:03:49,600 --> 01:03:51,400
Rym: I just want more game with the funny.

1124
01:03:51,480 --> 01:03:55,880
Scott: They are coming out with a DLC that's gonna add more Portal chambers, so, hurrah.

1125
01:03:56,280 --> 01:04:18,480
Rym: Because I did really, I think my favorite environmental part of the game is the huge shift when you find, you know, the original Aperture Science and Cave Johnson in the 50s, and how all the technology changes, like you find the 50s and the 60s and the 70s and the 80s and the 90s, and just like all the old infrastructure and how it gives you this impression of this huge area to explore.

1126
01:04:18,620 --> 01:04:25,100
Rym: And actually, that was some of the most interesting puzzles, was just trying to get up through all those ruins.

1127
01:04:26,061 --> 01:04:30,753
Scott: The only thing is that, what I was trying to say before, is that the atmosphere of the game, right, is I liked?

1128
01:04:30,813 --> 01:04:36,780
Scott: in Portal 1, even though GLaDOS is talking to you, it was a lot more quiet and alone in a Metroid kind of way.

1129
01:04:37,620 --> 01:04:39,459
Rym: Most of the Cave Johnson part was like that.

1130
01:04:39,800 --> 01:04:40,900
Scott: No, cause not really.

1131
01:04:40,960 --> 01:04:44,740
Rym: No, you're forgetting, there's the parts where you're going through a bunch of test chambers.

1132
01:04:45,240 --> 01:04:49,380
Rym: There's also the whole part where you're just in that gigantic area just trying to get up.

1133
01:04:49,800 --> 01:05:00,080
Scott: Well that very first, they talk about that in the commentary, how the very first time you go down in there, and when they try to give you that to make you feel, but that's just one part.

1134
01:05:00,440 --> 01:05:02,480
Scott: You know, it's not like you felt that way for the whole game.

1135
01:05:03,161 --> 01:05:06,980
Rym: Well I don't want to feel the same way the whole game, cause I felt that in Portal 1, I wanted a different atmosphere.

1136
01:05:07,240 --> 01:05:14,680
Scott: See, the thing is I like that alone in the dark Metroid kind of action, and I'm really disappointed, Metroid even got rid of it.

1137
01:05:14,760 --> 01:05:22,180
Rym: See, now in the Cave Johnson part though, the fact that it wasn't a real person talking to you anymore, it literally was just recordings, you were still completely alone.

1138
01:05:22,560 --> 01:05:25,500
Scott: Yeah, it's true, but you didn't feel the same Metroid-ness.

1139
01:05:26,141 --> 01:05:27,680
Rym: I don't know, I think you're obsessed with Metroid.

1140
01:05:27,720 --> 01:05:37,819
Scott: I don't know, I just like it when games, you know, it's like Nintendo had something right, they make Link not talk, and they make Samus not have anyone else with her.

1141
01:05:38,940 --> 01:05:40,472
Rym: That's true, that's a good move.

1142
01:05:41,960 --> 01:05:49,400
Rym: I love the Animal King, I like how you get to see him at the end, I love the fact that you see him back there, and he is the Animal King.

1143
01:05:49,763 --> 01:05:51,560
Rym: You know, King of the Portals?

1144
01:05:51,820 --> 01:05:51,955
Scott: I know.

1145
01:05:52,644 --> 01:05:54,180
Rym: Well, King of the... Turrets.

1146
01:05:54,500 --> 01:05:57,940
Rym: Yeah, and the bit where you find the defective turrets, then you swap it out.

1147
01:05:58,500 --> 01:06:02,360
Scott: Yeah, actually, that part, the first time through, cause I did it twice, cause I did commentary.

1148
01:06:02,480 --> 01:06:05,520
Rym: I saved a turret before I was supposed to, and I carried him.

1149
01:06:05,760 --> 01:06:09,540
Scott: Exactly, the first time I did it, I saved the turret, and I thought I had done something clever.

1150
01:06:09,880 --> 01:06:16,820
Scott: And then when I went through doing the commentary, and I got to the same part, and realized that I would have had to do that no matter what, I was like, oh.

1151
01:06:17,381 --> 01:06:18,660
Scott: I thought I had done a clever, different...

1152
01:06:18,660 --> 01:06:23,777
Rym: But I love how every time Wheatley's like, don't look, he's pretty much, either doesn't have a solution, or...

1153
01:06:24,560 --> 01:06:25,279
Scott: Or he brute forces it stupidly.

1154
01:06:25,320 --> 01:06:26,078
Scott: Yeah, he just like, breaks it.

1155
01:06:26,580 --> 01:06:34,500
Rym: But when he's trying to, quote unquote, hack the neurotoxin, and there's a lot of dialogue, I waited for a while, and just watched him just saying stuff.

1156
01:06:35,340 --> 01:06:38,100
Rym: I don't even know how long it went on, I gave up and just solved the puzzle.

1157
01:06:38,140 --> 01:06:45,520
Scott: The thing is, you can just go and get the, I didn't bother waiting to listen to dialogue, cause you can go listen to all the dialogue on YouTube, cause some people extracted it from the files.

1158
01:06:45,760 --> 01:06:46,040
Scott: Yeah, yeah.

1159
01:06:47,201 --> 01:06:49,960
Scott: Alright, yeah, Portal 2, if you haven't played Portal 1, play that.

1160
01:06:50,140 --> 01:06:51,020
Rym: It was a triumph.

1161
01:06:51,360 --> 01:06:53,540
Scott: If you haven't played Portal 2, play that after.

1162
01:06:54,681 --> 01:07:01,360
Scott: It's a no-brainer, even at the full price of 40 bucks, but if you're cheap, there's no reason not to wait if you've got someone to do the co-op with later.

1163
01:07:01,520 --> 01:07:04,080
Rym: And you don't care about everybody making jokes about space!

1164
01:07:04,600 --> 01:07:09,600
Scott: And you don't care about, yeah, then, you know, just buy it later when it's inevitably gonna be 20 bucks or whatever.

1165
01:07:09,600 --> 01:07:18,480
Rym: I mean, seriously, you might have forgotten, or you might be young, when Portal 1 came out, it was, like, one of the greatest, like, revolutionary games ever.

1166
01:07:18,940 --> 01:07:21,169
Scott: Yeah, and there's no other game like it, right?

1167
01:07:21,189 --> 01:07:23,700
Scott: You know, we always complain about all these games being genre-fied.

1168
01:07:23,740 --> 01:07:29,220
Rym: Portal 1 and Portal 2 are, in my opinion, literally some of the greatest games ever made.

1169
01:07:29,280 --> 01:07:32,697
Scott: Do you know any other FPS puzzle platformers?

1170
01:07:32,777 --> 01:07:33,320
Scott: I don't know any.

1171
01:07:33,680 --> 01:07:37,942
Rym: Well, you could argue that many aspects of Half-Life 1 and 2.

1172
01:07:37,942 --> 01:07:40,519
Scott: Are platformers, but not puzzle platformers.

1173
01:07:41,941 --> 01:07:44,820
Rym: Some specific areas were puzzle platformers.

1174
01:07:45,020 --> 01:07:45,357
Scott: Like what?

1175
01:07:46,840 --> 01:07:48,800
Scott: Half-Life 2 has a couple physics puzzles.

1176
01:07:48,920 --> 01:07:54,640
Rym: In Half-Life 1, I remember a room where you can enter coordinates to blow shit up on the map.

1177
01:07:55,366 --> 01:07:55,660
Scott: Okay.

1178
01:07:56,120 --> 01:08:01,860
Rym: And you have to figure out a sequence of things to blow up while jumping between different areas to get out.

1179
01:08:02,884 --> 01:08:03,093
Scott: Uh-huh.

1180
01:08:03,849 --> 01:08:04,040
Scott: Yeah.

1181
01:08:04,641 --> 01:08:06,680
Scott: That's not exactly a Portal puzzle.

1182
01:08:06,985 --> 01:08:08,020
Rym: I didn't say Portal puzzle.

1183
01:08:08,240 --> 01:08:09,599
Scott: It was not a platforming puzzle either.

1184
01:08:09,780 --> 01:08:10,780
Rym: There was platforming involved.

1185
01:08:11,080 --> 01:08:12,480
Scott: Yeah, but it's not a platforming puzzle.

1186
01:08:13,386 --> 01:08:14,379
Rym: I would argue that it kind of was.

1187
01:08:16,126 --> 01:08:17,439
Scott: Anyway, that wasn't the whole game, right?

1188
01:08:17,921 --> 01:08:19,180
Rym: Anyway, let's go one step further.

1189
01:08:19,560 --> 01:08:24,979
Rym: In the modern era, Valve is probably the most consistently great gaming company there is.

1190
01:08:25,279 --> 01:08:27,437
Scott: Except for Blizzard, but I'm not a fan of them.

1191
01:08:27,779 --> 01:08:30,859
Rym: They're not my kind of game, but they're consistently great for what they are.

1192
01:08:30,961 --> 01:08:31,819
Rym: So, yeah, you know what?

1193
01:08:31,939 --> 01:08:38,180
Rym: Valve and Blizzard are probably the best gaming companies from actual game design perspectives.

1194
01:08:38,420 --> 01:08:40,658
Scott: Oh, and if you're pla- Oh, one last thing while we end this show.

1195
01:08:41,140 --> 01:08:44,800
Scott: If you're playing Portal on an Xbox or a PS3, you suck.

